  "notes": "This is a natural experiment study exploiting Italy's ChatGPT ban (April 1, 2023) in a difference-in-differences framework. The paper examines heterogeneous effects by worker experience level (less experienced vs. experienced developers) and by package contributor status. Key findings: the ban increased output quantity and quality for less experienced users but had negative effects on routine tasks for experienced users. The study documents evidence of users circumventing the ban using VPNs (52.2 percentage point increase in VPN searches on April 3; 20.6 percentage points higher on average over the workweek) and TOR bridges (approximately 9.4 percentage points increase in user numbers on average). The authors note that access to other NLP-powered tools (GitHub Copilot, Claude, Bard) was not affected by the ban, and that many ways existed to circumvent the ban. Pre-trend tests (joint F-test) were not rejected at conventional levels for any outcome. Placebo treatment effects were insignificant. Results were robust to alternative outcome measures and to excluding users from each control country. Output quantity and quality retained significance after correcting for multiple hypothesis testing. The study provides evidence only on very short-run effects due to the ban's short duration and ease of circumvention.",
